  <!-- Licensing and Safety -->
  <section class="px-6 py-12" id="licensing">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="font-[Space_Grotesk] text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8">
        LICENSING AND <span class="text-[#FAFF00]">SAFETY</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="max-w-3xl space-y-6 font-[Public_Sans] text-[#D4D4D4] text-base leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          Crypto casino licensing varies widely. Some jurisdictions enforce strict player protections. Others are barely more than a rubber stamp. Knowing the difference protects your deposits.
        </p>

        <div>
          <h3 class="font-[Space_Grotesk] text-xl font-bold text-[#39FF14] mb-3">Tier 1: Strict Regulation</h3>
          <p class="mb-3">
            The <a href="https://www.mga.org.mt" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-[#39FF14] underline underline-offset-4 decoration-2 hover:text-white transition-colors">Malta Gaming Authority (MGA)</a> allows crypto under conditions aligned with the EU's MiCA framework. MGA licensees must segregate player funds, maintain dispute resolution processes, and submit to regular audits. If a casino holds an MGA license, your money has real regulatory protection behind it.
          </p>
          <p class="mb-3">
            The <a href="https://www.gamblingcommission.gov.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-[#39FF14] underline underline-offset-4 decoration-2 hover:text-white transition-colors">UK Gambling Commission (UKGC)</a> is considered the gold standard for gambling regulation. It does not currently allow crypto payments for licensed operators. The UKGC has been exploring crypto integration as of 2026, but no licensed UK casino accepts Bitcoin deposits today.
          </p>
          <p>
            The <a href="https://www.isleofmangsc.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-[#39FF14] underline underline-offset-4 decoration-2 hover:text-white transition-colors">Isle of Man Gambling Supervision Commission</a> is explicitly crypto-friendly with strong player protections. It requires operators to hold player funds in segregated accounts and maintain clear responsible gambling policies. One of the better options for crypto casino regulation.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="font-[Space_Grotesk] text-xl font-bold text-[#FAFF00] mb-3">Tier 2: Moderate Regulation</h3>
          <p class="mb-3">
            The <a href="https://www.cga.cw" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-[#39FF14] underline underline-offset-4 decoration-2 hover:text-white transition-colors">Curacao Gaming Authority (CGA)</a> underwent a major overhaul in December 2024. The old sub-license system that allowed master license holders to sell sub-licenses with minimal oversight was abolished. New direct licensing requires actual compliance, KYC/AML procedures, and real operational standards. Crypto is fully permitted. The new regime is a genuine improvement, though enforcement track record is still being established.
          </p>
          <p>
            The <a href="https://gamingcommission.ca" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-[#39FF14] underline underline-offset-4 decoration-2 hover:text-white transition-colors">Kahnawake Gaming Commission</a> has been regulating online gambling since 1996, making it one of the oldest authorities in the space. It is crypto-friendly and maintains a reasonable complaint resolution process. Not as rigorous as MGA or Isle of Man, but a legitimate regulator with decades of operational history.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="font-[Space_Grotesk] text-xl font-bold text-white mb-3">Tier 3: Proceed with Caution</h3>
          <p>
            Some licenses carry real legitimacy concerns. Anjouan (Comoros) has been flagged by legal analysts for potential conflicts with local law, and FATF monitoring adds another layer of risk. If a casino's only license is from a jurisdiction you have never heard of, verify it directly with the issuing authority before depositing. A license number on a website footer means nothing if the regulator does not actually confirm it. When in doubt, stick with casinos holding Tier 1 or Tier 2 licenses.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

